import java.util.*;

class Solution {
    private int m, n, total;
    private Map<Integer, Integer> map;
    private Random rand;

    public Solution(int m, int n) {
        this.m = m;
        this.n = n;
        this.total = m * n;
        this.map = new HashMap<>();
        this.rand = new Random();
    }

    public int[] flip() {
        int idx = rand.nextInt(total--);
        int actual = map.getOrDefault(idx, idx);
        int last = map.getOrDefault(total, total);
        map.put(idx, last);
        return new int[]{actual / n, actual % n};
    }

    public void reset() {
        total = m * n;
        map.clear();
    }
}
```
efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(1) per flip/reset
space complexity: O(k) where k is number of flipped cells
energy implications: LOW
explanation: Uses Fisher-Yates reservoir sampling with a hash map to map virtual indices to actual indices, ensuring uniform randomness with only one random call per flip. Space grows linearly with flipped cells, but remains minimal due to sparse storage.

